<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="procurement-management">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>pm</group>
    <domain>pm-traditional</domain>
    <summary>Structured vendor engagement: make-or-buy decisions, SOW authoring, contract type selection, vendor evaluation, and performance monitoring.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>procurement</tag>
      <tag>vendor-management</tag>
      <tag>contracts</tag>
      <tag>sow</tag>
      <tag>sourcing</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Procurement Management</title>
    <summary>Structured vendor engagement: make-or-buy decisions, Statement of Work authoring, contract type selection, vendor evaluation scoring, and ongoing performance monitoring. Every external engagement needs a written SOW with testable acceptance criteria before a contract is signed.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Vague SOWs and wrong contract types are the leading causes of vendor disputes and cost overruns. Fixed-price contracts with poorly defined scope push vendors to minimise effort; T&amp;M contracts without caps leave buyers with open-ended risk. A structured procurement process forces clarity upfront and transfers the right level of risk to the right party.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Engaging external vendors, agencies, or contractors for work worth more than a minor purchase</item>
        <item>Choosing between building internally versus buying a service or product</item>
        <item>Preparing RFI / RFP / RFQ packages and vendor evaluation matrices</item>
        <item>Selecting contract type given scope clarity and risk tolerance</item>
        <item>Monitoring vendor deliverables against signed SOW milestones</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Sub-$1k one-off SaaS purchases — overhead exceeds value; use a credit card and receipt</item>
        <item>Open-source dependencies with no vendor relationship — treat as supply-chain risk, not procurement</item>
        <item>Internal cross-charging between business units — uses transfer pricing rules, not procurement contracts</item>
        <item>Highly regulated public-sector procurements (FAR/DFARS/EU directives) — methodology omits mandatory regulatory clauses</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="Make-or-Buy Decision">
      <rule>
        <statement>Decide make-vs-buy before writing any SOW. Evaluate cost, control, speed, expertise, and risk transfer explicitly.</statement>
        <rationale>Skipping this step leads to outsourcing work that should be internal (losing IP) or building internally when a vendor is cheaper and faster.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <p>Key factors: fixed vs variable cost, control level, access to specialist expertise, risk ownership, and long-term switching cost. Switching cost is routinely underestimated — factor in knowledge transfer, vendor lock-in, and transition time.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Statement of Work">
      <rule>
        <statement>Every external engagement requires a SOW with: scope (in and out), numbered deliverables, acceptance criteria per deliverable, milestone dates, and payment tied to acceptance not activity.</statement>
        <rationale>Vague SOWs are the top cause of scope disputes. Acceptance-linked payment aligns vendor incentives with buyer outcomes.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="bad">
        <note>SOW says "develop the mobile app to a high standard" — no deliverables listed, no acceptance criteria, payment on delivery date.</note>
      </example>
      <example type="good">
        <note>SOW lists D1 (design mockups, accepted when stakeholder sign-off), D2 (working app, accepted when App Store approval + 95% crash-free rate), payment 25% / 50% / 25% at milestone acceptance.</note>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Contract Type Selection">
      <rule>
        <statement>Choose FFP when scope is at least 80% defined; T&amp;M with a NOT-TO-EXCEED cap when scope is evolving; CPFF only for research with inherently unknowable cost.</statement>
        <rationale>FFP without defined scope incentivises vendors to minimise effort. Uncapped T&amp;M transfers all cost risk to the buyer. CPFF for routine work is fiscally irresponsible.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Any T&amp;M contract must include a weekly burn report and a hard cap. Uncapped T&amp;M is open-ended risk.</statement>
        <rationale>Without a cap, T&amp;M scope creep is invisible until the invoice arrives.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Vendor Sourcing">
      <p>Use the right sourcing instrument: RFI to gather market info, RFP for formal solution proposals, RFQ for price quotes on defined work, sole-source only when justified with documented rationale.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Require references AND a structured reference-call rubric. References without a rubric are positive-bias noise.</statement>
        <rationale>Vendors select their best references; a structured interview reveals actual weaknesses.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Vendor Management">
      <rule>
        <statement>Track deliverables against SOW, reconcile invoices against milestones, and maintain a quarterly vendor scorecard (on-time %, defect rate, escalation count). Renew or churn based on data.</statement>
        <rationale>Set-and-forget vendor management is the second most common procurement failure mode after vague SOWs.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Negotiate exit terms before signing: notice period, data handback, transition assistance, IP transfer. Trapped-buyer is the most common contract failure mode.</statement>
        <rationale>Renegotiating exit terms after the relationship sours produces the worst outcomes for both parties.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Weighted Scoring">
      <rule>
        <statement>Define evaluation criteria and weights before receiving proposals; changing weights after seeing proposals anchors the result.</statement>
        <rationale>Post-hoc weight adjustment is a well-documented anchoring bias — it reverse-engineers justification for a predetermined winner.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Run sensitivity analysis: shift each top weight by ±5% and verify the winner does not flip. If it does, the decision margin is too small to be reliable without deeper due diligence.</statement>
        <rationale>A margin below 5% in a weighted matrix is statistical noise, not a defensible decision.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Evaluation Antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Lowest-price wins: selecting the cheapest vendor without weighting quality, experience, and risk.</description>
        <reason>Price is the most legible criterion but the weakest predictor of delivery success. Low-price vendors frequently compensate by minimising scope or requesting change orders.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Acceptance criteria written as subjective goals ("high quality code", "good performance").</description>
        <reason>Subjective criteria cannot be evaluated at acceptance time, creating disputes. Require testable thresholds: defect density, response time, test coverage percentage.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Evaluation matrix weighted at 5–10% for references, then not interviewing references in a structured way.</description>
        <reason>References are positive-bias by selection; without a rubric the criterion adds no information and can be gamed.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Multi-supplier / prime + sub arrangements treated as a single-vendor procurement.</description>
        <reason>Partner ecosystems require separate SOWs, liability chains, and IP ownership clauses per party. Combining them obscures accountability.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="Legal Clauses the Agent Cannot Generate">
      <rule>
        <statement>Always flag legal review required on: limitation of liability cap, indemnification scope, IP ownership, data residency, sub-processor terms, jurisdiction, and termination for convenience.</statement>
        <rationale>LLMs default to US-style clauses and miss EU GDPR processor terms, HIPAA BAAs, and jurisdiction-specific UWG/MAC provisions. Legal review is non-negotiable.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Agentic Workflow">
      <p>The agent is a procurement document drafter and evaluator. Inputs: scope doc + budget + risk profile → outputs SOW, RFP, evaluation matrix, draft contract clause set. A second agent ingests vendor responses (PDF / DOCX) and emits a side-by-side comparison + scored matrix. A third agent monitors live engagements (deliverable status, invoice variance) and flags drift. Humans own all final selections, contract signatures, and dispute escalation.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Recommended Subagents">
      <list>
        <item>sow-drafter — turns scope doc into SOW skeleton with deliverables, acceptance criteria, milestones, payment schedule.</item>
        <item>rfp-builder — composes RFP package (background, scope, requirements, response format, evaluation criteria, timeline).</item>
        <item>proposal-comparator — ingests vendor PDFs, normalises against RFP fields, outputs matrix.</item>
        <item>vendor-monitor — reads invoices + status reports + milestone deliverables, emits health RAG and variance flags.</item>
        <item>make-vs-buy-analyst — TCO model with switching cost and lock-in factor.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Prompt Pattern">
      <p>Inputs:</p>
      <list>
        <item>scope.md: business need + functional requirements</item>
        <item>budget_usd: cap</item>
        <item>timeline: weeks_to_kickoff, target_delivery</item>
        <item>risk_profile: low | medium | high (drives contract type)</item>
        <item>jurisdictions: ["US-CA", "EU-DE", ...]</item>
      </list>
      <p>Output JSON:</p>
      <code lang="json"><![CDATA[{
  "recommended_contract_type": "FFP|T&M|T&M_cap|CPFF|CPIF",
  "rationale": "...",
  "sow": {
    "scope_in":[...],
    "scope_out":[...],
    "deliverables":[{"id","name","acceptance_criteria","due"}],
    "milestones":[{"name","date","payment_pct"}]
  },
  "rfp": {
    "evaluation_criteria":[{"name","weight"}],
    "response_format": {...}
  },
  "required_legal_clauses": ["IP", "indemnity", "LoL cap",
                             "data residency", "termination", "audit"],
  "open_questions_for_legal": [...]
}]]></code>
      <p>Rules:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Always flag legal review required.</item>
        <item>No invented vendor names.</item>
        <item>For risk_profile=high, prefer FFP only if scope is ≥80% defined.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="CLI Tools">
      <list>
        <item>pdfplumber / pypdf — Parse vendor proposals + invoices</item>
        <item>pandoc — Convert SOW markdown → DOCX/PDF for signature workflow</item>
        <item>git + git-lfs — Version-control SOW + redlines</item>
        <item>docusign-cli (community) — Send SOW for signature</item>
        <item>openpyxl — Generate evaluation matrix in Excel</item>
        <item>xmllint — Validate UBL / e-invoicing XML</item>
        <item>currency-converter — FX for multi-jurisdiction SOWs</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Services and Apps">
      <list>
        <item>Coupa — Enterprise procure-to-pay (REST API)</item>
        <item>SAP Ariba — Source-to-pay, sourcing events (REST/SOAP)</item>
        <item>Ivalua — Spend management (REST)</item>
        <item>Procurify / Tropic — SaaS-spend management for SMB (REST)</item>
        <item>Vendr / Sastrify — SaaS contract negotiation as a service (API)</item>
        <item>DocuSign / PandaDoc — Contract signing (REST)</item>
        <item>Ironclad / LinkSquares — CLM with AI clause extraction (REST)</item>
        <item>Bill.com — Invoice + payment automation (REST)</item>
        <item>Spendesk / Ramp — Card + invoice spend (REST)</item>
        <item>Notion / Confluence — SOW templates (REST)</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Best Practices">
      <list>
        <item>Always pair FFP with a strong change-control clause; without it, fixed price becomes "vendor minimises scope".</item>
        <item>T&amp;M needs a NOT-TO-EXCEED cap and weekly burn report; uncapped T&amp;M is open-ended risk.</item>
        <item>Require references and a reference-call rubric — references are positive bias unless interviewed structured.</item>
        <item>Negotiate exit terms before signing: notice period, data hand-back, transition assistance, IP transfer. Trapped-buyer is the most common procurement failure mode.</item>
        <item>Tie payment to acceptance, not to milestones — milestone-based payment without acceptance criteria is "pay for activity, not value".</item>
        <item>Build a vendor scorecard quarterly (on-time delivery %, defect rate, escalation count). Renew or churn based on data, not relationship.</item>
        <item>Keep an MSA + SOW model: MSA covers legal terms once, SOWs add scope per engagement. Avoids re-negotiating IP/indemnity each time.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="AI-agent Gotchas">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Legal clauses are jurisdiction-specific; LLMs default to US-style clauses and miss EU GDPR processor terms, UK MAC clauses, German UWG provisions.</description>
        <reason>Always require legal review for cross-border SOWs; do not rely on agent-drafted clauses.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Indemnification caps drift: agents draft "uncapped" indemnification by default — require explicit cap (often 1x or 2x annual fees).</description>
        <reason>Review every generated contract clause for liability caps before sharing with vendors.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Data residency / sub-processor language is missing from generic LLM SOW templates; mandatory for GDPR, HIPAA, SOC 2 buyers.</description>
        <reason>If compliance is required, specify it in the agent prompt explicitly.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Currency drift in multi-region SOWs: agents put a USD figure in a EU SOW without an exchange clause; demand price-adjustment language.</description>
        <reason>Lock exchange rates or add an explicit price-adjustment clause for multi-currency SOWs.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Make-vs-buy bias: agents tend to recommend "buy" for software (training data favours SaaS marketing); explicitly weight switching cost and IP ownership.</description>
        <reason>Provide explicit guidance on make-vs-buy weighting before agent analysis.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Vendor-name hallucination is common in shortlist drafting; always require a user-supplied vendor list, never let the agent invent.</description>
        <reason>Supply a curated vendor list as agent input; never let it generate candidate names.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Evaluation matrix can be reverse-engineered: if you tell an LLM the answer, it will weight the criteria to justify it. Lock weights before scoring.</description>
        <reason>Define and commit to evaluation weights before receiving proposals.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Acceptance criteria written by agents are often subjective ("high quality"); demand testable criteria (% test coverage, defect density, response time).</description>
        <reason>Review every acceptance criterion for objectivity and testability before signing SOW.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/sow.md" purpose="Statement of Work skeleton with scope, deliverables, acceptance criteria, payment schedule"/>
      <template path="templates/vendor-scoring.py" purpose="Weighted vendor score calculator with sensitivity check"/>
    </templates>
    <see-also>
      <link href="https://www.pmi.org/pmbok-guide"/>
      <link href="https://www.iso.org/standard/63026.html"/>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
